@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "About Futakuchi Mana";
}

<div class="container py-5">
    <div class="text-center mb-5">
        <h1 class="display-3 about-title mb-4">About Futakuchi Mana</h1>
        <p class="lead text-center">
            Explore the world of Futakuchi Mana, a two-mouthed woman and Virtual Singer.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="row align-items-center mb-5 about-section">
        <div class="col-md-6 order-md-2 text-center">
            <img src="~/img/About/Futakuchi_Mana_about1.jpg" alt="Futakuchi Mana Portrait" class="img-fluid about-img rounded-circle border border-danger p-2" />
        </div>
        <div class="col-md-6 order-md-1">
            <h2 class="section-heading mt-4 mt-md-0">Who is Futakuchi Mana?</h2>
            <p>
                Mana's official profession is Best Head Torturer of Hell, which she fulfills besides being a VSinger. She once stated that she works as a Head Torturer by day and a mumble rapper at night. She often posts raw vocal practice sessions on her official YouTube channel apart from karaoke streams, watch-alongs, song covers, memes and video shitposts. She is very honest with her opinions and is strict when enforcing rules in her community, but is not short of cracking jokes and appreciating the presence and effort of fans.
            </p>
            <p>
                Mana had always stated that the support she had received as a VSinger and content creator had been overwhelming from the time she debuted. To her, being a VSinger is a hobby and release from the grind as Head Torturer. Despite her busy schedule, she makes it a point to check in on her fans, the Imps, and share stories and experiences with them.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <hr class="about-divider">

    <div class="row align-items-center mb-5 about-section">
        <div class="col-md-6 text-center">
            <img src="~/img/About/Futakuchi_Mana_about2.jpg" alt="Futakuchi Mana Logo" class="img-fluid about-img rounded-3 border border-danger p-2" />
        </div>
        <div class="col-md-6">
            <h2 class="section-heading mt-4 mt-md-0">The Music Style</h2>
            <p>
                Futakuchi Mana is best known for her metal cover arrangements of popular J-pop and Vocaloid songs, including powerful renditions of “Ussewa” by Ado and “KING” by Kanaria. Her music blends aggressive instrumentals with haunting vocals, creating an intense and emotionally charged atmosphere that resonates with both metalheads and anime fans alike.
            </p>
            <p>
                Outside of covers, Mana experiments with mumble rap and layered vocal harmonies, often showcasing her raw vocal practice sessions during streams. Her versatility as a VSinger stems from her fearless approach to genre fusion, resulting in a sound that is dark, chaotic, yet strangely beautiful.
            </p>
            <p class="text-center mt-4">
                <a asp-controller="Music" asp-action="Music" class="btn btn-primary btn-lg custom-btn-red">
                    <i class="fas fa-arrow-right me-2"></i> Explore Music
                </a>
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <hr class="about-divider">

    <div class="row align-items-center about-section">
        <div class="col-md-6 order-md-2 text-center">
            <img src="~/img/About/Futakuchi_Mana_about3.png" alt="Futakuchi Mana Appearance" class="img-fluid about-img rounded-3 border border-danger p-2" />
        </div>
        <div class="col-md-6 order-md-1">
            <h2 class="section-heading mt-4 mt-md-0">Appearance</h2>
            <p>
                Mana’s appearance is deeply inspired by gothic lolita aesthetics and Japanese yokai lore. With a signature red-and-black color scheme, she often dons traditional elements like hairpins, horns, and ceremonial patterns that nod to her mythological roots as a Futakuchi-onna—a woman with a second mouth on the back of her head.
            </p>
            <p>
                Her visual identity is both elegant and unsettling, exuding an eerie charisma. Whether drawn in soft watercolor or sharp digital lines, Mana is instantly recognizable through her crimson eyes, dual expression themes, and the subtle symbolism woven into every outfit and art piece.
            </p>
            <p class="text-center mt-4">
                <a asp-controller="Shop" asp-action="Shop" class="btn btn-primary btn-lg custom-btn-red">
                    <i class="fas fa-arrow-right me-2"></i> Explore Collections
                </a>
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <hr class="about-divider">

    <div class="row flex-column about-section text-center">
        <div class="col">
            <h2 class="section-heading mt-4">Imps</h2>
            <p>
                Mana affectionately calls her fanbase the Imps. More than just viewers, they’re an active part of her creative journey. The Imps have been instrumental in community-driven projects like the “International Metal Project” (I.M.P.), collaborating with Mana to produce original music and promotional content.
            </p>
            <p>
                Despite her hellish persona, Mana makes a point of interacting with fans regularly—whether through community shoutouts, meme reactions, or heartfelt monologues during streams. The bond she fosters with her Imps is rooted in mutual respect, creative collaboration, and a shared love for all things weird and wonderful.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="col mt-4">
            <img src="~/img/About/Futakuchi_Mana_about4.png" alt="Futakuchi Mana with Imp" class="img-fluid about-img rounded-circle border border-danger p-2 w-25" />
        </div>
    </div>
</div>